[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4
{ To play a gambit is to sacrifice material, usually a pawn, right in the opening. This is done to get something in return = compensation. The concept of compensation is essential in understanding gambit play. In general, a good principle to keep in mind is:   To understand a gambit, you have to know what the compensation consists in! Thus, to know how to play a gambit you need to know what your compensation is and how to exploit it. To know how to play against a gambit you need to know what your opponent's compensation is and how to negate it.  Now, a gambit is sound when its compensation is objectively sufficient. What this means is that even with best play  (correspondence play, computer analysis etc.)  neither side is better or worse than usual. In other words, when you play a gambit with White it is sound when you retain at least your usual advantage. When you play a gambit with Black it is sound when you have no more than your usual disadvantage.  Of course, most gambits are not sound. However, some, like the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, are nevertheless pretty good. A gambit is good when it is not fully sound, but works well in practical play. Some of the reasons why are the same as in the case of non-gambit sidelines or rare openings:  - Your opponent won't know the frequently unintuitive best line and plays something intuitive, but 2nd-rate  - You have more experience with the ensuing types of positions than your opponent  - There is a psychologically unsettling effect in having to face the unfamiliar  However, good gambits work for further sorts of reasons:  - A good gambit puts your opponent under some sort of pressure, forcing them to face concrete threats   - Best gambits feature an unintuitive & narrow path to equality or an advantage.  - The unintuitiveness means that the relevant moves are harder to remember and hard or impossible to find over the board  - The narrowness means that only specific moves will do, otherwise your opponent will be at a considerable disadvantage  Now, even though the BDG is a pretty good gambit, I wouldn't make it a mainstay in your repertoire for over, say, 1800, in Classical games where your opponent can prepare for you...  But things are very different in fast time controls  (e. g. Blitz, Rapid)  where your opponent CAN'T prepare for you. In such situations, the BDG is a great weapon since it usually gives you a big initiative, forces them into a tactical dogfight from the get-go, features a clear & rehearsed attacking plan, and has a high likelihood of causing your opponent to burn lots of clock time.  Relatedly, I have one comment about the way this repertoire is built up. A lot the theory of the BDG that eventually made it to Scheerer's book was developed in correspondence games up to the early to mid-2000s. In many ways, the BDG is a pre-computer era correspondence opening. But some of what's ok in correspondence is not good for fast time controls  (e. g. you wouldn't necessarily want to play super messy lines with your own king under attack...)  .   The idea in this repertoire is to strike a balance between what's objectively strongest, what's nettlesome for Black, and what's practical. Thus, even though there are many lines where we go for standard theory and improve upon it  (e. g. Euwe, Teichmann)  , there are also some lines where we go for shortcut sidelines since the main lines are just not good for White or at best very double-edged with lots to learn. I will comment on this in more depth once the relevant moments come up. }
