{ For   6...c5  seek out the game Ashley vs Shabalov, 1994. } 7. Ne2
{ Why this move? As Waitzkin puts it in one of his old Chessmaster videos, in this position Black's idea is to give White an isolated queen's pawn and then play ...Nbd7 to ...Nb6 to ...Nd5. White's idea with Nge2 is to be able to play Nf4 and challenge Black's control over  d5  , if needed.  For this plan in effect, see the model game Waitzkin vs. Moskow. }
